And we give them a wallet card and also instruct them to take Tylenol and dexamethasone formula.

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:34.140
And this is sort of our SOP for management of CRS and ICANTS.

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:37.920
And it depends on whether patients are neutropenic or not.

00:03:38.140 --> 00:03:45.580
If one has a grade 1 CRS and they're not neutropenic, they will take their Tylenol and dexamethasone.

00:03:45.780 --> 00:03:52.980
And then we'll come into the infusion center the next day and get cultures and reassess to see if they need anything else.

00:03:52.980 --> 00:03:58.800
If they are neutropenic, then they're instructed to go to the ED.

00:03:59.180 --> 00:04:01.600
Or call or on-call as soon as possible.

00:04:01.780 --> 00:04:11.760
And then we try to give all of those measures like TOC's and cultures and diabetics in the infusion center prior to them going to the ED or getting admitted.

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:18.040
Grade 2 CRS and any ICANTS will prioritize to go to the ED or be admitted.

00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:28.920
So we have treated 14 patients with multiple myeloma among all the other Bispecific therapies.

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:29.840
As an outpatient.

00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:33.820
And those include 15 different Bispecific.

00:04:33.820 --> 00:04:37.120
2 teclizumab, 4 Elra, and 9 talconamab.

00:04:37.580 --> 00:04:40.700
And you see that most of them had lower grade CRS.

00:04:41.380 --> 00:04:43.880
Grade 1 to 2 in 7 of 15 patients.

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:49.600
No grade 2 to 4 CRS and no ICANTS in these populations.

00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:57.260
But I thought it's interesting that 7 of these patients also ended up going to the hospital.

00:04:58.900 --> 00:05:02.540
Mostly unrelated to CRS or ICANTS and they were infectious complications.

00:05:03.280 --> 00:05:12.200
And one person related to CRS and ICANTS which I think stresses the importance of monitoring these patients very closely for other complications as well.

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:19.680
Some of the barriers to outpatient administration that we have noticed is patients who don't have a caregiver.

00:05:20.920 --> 00:05:25.160
Patients who do not have transportation to come back and forth or live far away.

00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:28.760
Those patients who have large disease burden and we're worried about.

00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:31.100
We're worried about higher risk of CRS and ICANTS.

00:05:31.980 --> 00:05:37.620
The older frailer population and a lot of people like the idea of quote unquote being monitored in the hospital.

00:05:37.620 --> 00:05:41.000
So that kind of limits our outpatient administration as well.

00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:45.440
So briefly about our IST.

00:05:45.980 --> 00:05:48.740
There are three main questions that we were trying to answer.

00:05:48.740 --> 00:05:52.500
Can Elra be safely administered as an outpatient in a controlled setting?

00:05:52.820 --> 00:05:55.220
Can Elra be used as earlier lines of therapy?

00:05:55.220 --> 00:05:56.720
1 to 3 prior lines of therapy?

00:05:58.620 --> 00:06:04.080
Can Elra be stopped if someone has a sustained MRD negativity?

00:06:06.380 --> 00:06:08.400
So these are the endpoints.

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:13.220
The primary endpoint being best overall MRD negativity rate at threshold 10 to the minus 5.

00:06:13.280 --> 00:06:20.100
And we have other secondary endpoints including the proportion of patients requiring admission due to adverse event in the first cycle.

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:23.600
And the safety outcomes as well.

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:28.080
In our study we do not have tocilizumab prophylaxis.

00:06:28.480 --> 00:06:37.820
And this was mainly FDA driven but we do the standard pre-medications with Tylenol, Benadryl, and dexamethasone.

00:06:37.820 --> 00:06:51.040
And we include the Elra doses are pretty standard but we do include a treatment free observation period in those people who achieve sustained MRD negativity for greater than 12 months.

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:58.340
And this was just open last year so we're hoping that we can update you on more results.

00:06:58.340 --> 00:07:00.900
in the future. Thank you so much.
